00:03:03.199 --> 00:03:04.460
How do I describe you?

00:03:04.560 --> 00:03:06.703
Like. what kind of title
should I give you?

00:03:06.803 --> 00:03:09.786
I'm a Saudi journalist. uh.

00:03:09.886 --> 00:03:11.748
self-exiled in Washington.

00:03:11.848 --> 00:03:13.871
[Faris as Khashoggi] I write
for The Washington Post.

00:03:13.971 --> 00:03:17.635
[woman] Okay. and why?
Why did you self-exile?

00:03:17.735 --> 00:03:19.357
[Faris as Khashoggi]
How breathtakingly fast

00:03:19.457 --> 00:03:23.121
you can fall out of favor.

00:03:23.221 --> 00:03:25.744
It is all quite shocking.

00:03:27.826 --> 00:03:32.291
Saudi Arabia is the only
home we know or want.

00:03:32.391 --> 00:03:34.393
yet we are the enemy.

00:03:36.235 --> 00:03:39.339
How did all this change?

00:03:39.439 --> 00:03:41.841
[engine rumbling]

00:03:45.486 --> 00:03:48.189
I was a teenager
in the 1970s

00:03:48.289 --> 00:03:52.353
and grew up in the markets
around the Prophet's Mosque.

00:03:52.453 --> 00:03:55.236
As a Saudi journalist
starting my career.

00:03:55.336 --> 00:03:59.041
I witnessed phenomenal
growth and expansion.

00:03:59.141 --> 00:04:02.284
Scholars and the people were
brimming with expectations.

00:04:02.384 --> 00:04:03.966
And the United States

00:04:04.066 --> 00:04:06.809
was our most important
trading partner.

00:04:06.909 --> 00:04:08.771
importer of Saudi oil

00:04:08.871 --> 00:04:11.675
and our main source
of weapons.

00:04:15.479 --> 00:04:17.541
[Rundell] The Saudi-American
relationship

00:04:17.641 --> 00:04:20.264
started as a commercial
relationship.

00:04:20.364 --> 00:04:25.049
The Saudis were a reservoir
of global energy.

00:04:27.052 --> 00:04:30.956
I was a foreign service
officer for 30 years.

00:04:31.056 --> 00:04:33.599
Basically. everybody
from Jimmy Carter

00:04:33.699 --> 00:04:35.701
to. uh. Barack Obama.

00:04:36.542 --> 00:04:37.844
There's really nobody--

00:04:37.944 --> 00:04:39.085
and I say that perhaps

00:04:39.185 --> 00:04:40.847
somewhat forcefully.
but it's true.

00:04:40.947 --> 00:04:42.489
that there is
no other American

00:04:42.589 --> 00:04:44.591
with my level of experience.

00:04:45.953 --> 00:04:48.135
The American government
really had no relations

00:04:48.235 --> 00:04:52.340
with Saudi Arabia until
what's today Chevron

00:04:52.440 --> 00:04:55.003
went there and began
to drill for oil.

00:04:58.206 --> 00:05:00.148
[Brennan] Administration
after administration.

00:05:00.248 --> 00:05:03.072
in the '50s. '60s. '70s.
'80s. '90s.

00:05:03.172 --> 00:05:07.036
wanted to make sure that
the government. uh. in Riyadh.

00:05:07.136 --> 00:05:10.200
uh. was going to be. uh.
one that was closely aligned

00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:12.302
with the United States.

00:05:13.263 --> 00:05:17.207
I was working
at the CIA in Saudi Arabia

00:05:17.307 --> 00:05:20.171
in the early 1980s.

00:05:20.271 --> 00:05:24.295
It was soon after King Fahd
rose to the throne.

00:05:24.395 --> 00:05:25.897
And during that period

00:05:25.997 --> 00:05:27.659
there was
a significant infusion

00:05:27.759 --> 00:05:31.904
of military support to
the fledging Saudi military.

00:05:32.004 --> 00:05:34.026
We were very concerned
about making sure

00:05:34.126 --> 00:05:36.509
the Saudi monarchy
was going to be stable.

00:05:36.609 --> 00:05:38.111
[indistinct chatter]

00:05:38.211 --> 00:05:40.714
[Wright]
Saudi Arabia is divided

00:05:40.814 --> 00:05:42.716
into the royals
and the nonroyals.

00:05:42.816 --> 00:05:44.277
and the royals own everything.

00:05:44.377 --> 00:05:47.041
You know. it's named
after their family.

00:05:47.141 --> 00:05:51.005
The whole kingdom
is Saudi Arabia.

00:05:51.105 --> 00:05:54.249
ruled by the sons
of King Abdulaziz

00:05:54.349 --> 00:05:56.531
for a hundred years.

00:05:56.631 --> 00:05:58.533
You can get totally lost

00:05:58.633 --> 00:06:01.737
in the Kremlinology
of the Saudi royal family.

00:06:01.837 --> 00:06:03.259
[indistinct chatter]

00:06:03.359 --> 00:06:06.582
But it's a family.
and they govern by consensus.

00:06:06.682 --> 00:06:09.265
There are spats
and there are factions.

00:06:09.365 --> 00:06:11.307
but until recently.

00:06:11.407 --> 00:06:13.970
decisions would be made
by consensus.

00:06:15.212 --> 00:06:18.235
And in the category
of nonroyals.

00:06:18.335 --> 00:06:21.018
Jamal Khashoggi
carried a lot of influence.

00:06:22.460 --> 00:06:24.762
I don't think there was
any place in Saudi Arabia

00:06:24.862 --> 00:06:27.085
that was closed to him.

00:06:27.185 --> 00:06:29.247
It wasn't just
that he was powerful.

00:06:29.347 --> 00:06:30.369
People liked him.

00:06:30.469 --> 00:06:31.730
[helicopter rotors whirring]

00:06:31.830 --> 00:06:34.533
Jamal had
an interesting analysis

00:06:34.633 --> 00:06:38.017
of the problems
of Saudi Arabia.

00:06:38.117 --> 00:06:39.859
We talked
about the schizophrenia

00:06:39.959 --> 00:06:42.422
that so many Saudis
had expressed to me.

00:06:42.522 --> 00:06:44.064
[indistinct chatter]

00:06:44.164 --> 00:06:46.386
It's undemocratic.
It's intolerant.

00:06:46.486 --> 00:06:49.830
It is one step
below a theocracy.

00:06:49.930 --> 00:06:51.872
From the beginning
of our relationship.

00:06:51.972 --> 00:06:55.436
America's had this tie
to this distinctly

00:06:55.536 --> 00:06:57.719
non-American entity

00:06:57.819 --> 00:07:01.363
and has enabled it.
up to this day. to survive.

00:07:01.463 --> 00:07:02.564
[man] speaking Arabic

00:07:02.664 --> 00:07:04.807
[Rundell] To call them
authoritarian

00:07:04.907 --> 00:07:08.090
is true in an absolute sense.

00:07:08.190 --> 00:07:10.974
but really.
most administrations

00:07:11.074 --> 00:07:13.216
who deal with Saudi Arabia
over time

00:07:13.316 --> 00:07:16.740
become aware of the fact
that Saudi Arabia

00:07:16.840 --> 00:07:20.264
is a valuable friend.
a valuable ally.

00:07:20.364 --> 00:07:23.027
and to throw that
under the bus is a bad idea.

00:07:23.127 --> 00:07:25.249
[call to prayer playing
over loudspeakers]

00:07:27.492 --> 00:07:30.035
[Wright] Saudi Arabia
was a part of the world

00:07:30.135 --> 00:07:32.277
that we didn't care about.
except for the oil.

00:07:32.377 --> 00:07:34.520
They can believe
what they want to believe

00:07:34.620 --> 00:07:36.642
as long as they keep pumping.

00:07:36.742 --> 00:07:39.045
But that totally changed

00:07:39.145 --> 00:07:41.127
when the Soviets
invaded Afghanistan

00:07:41.227 --> 00:07:42.969
in December '79.

00:07:43.069 --> 00:07:46.313
[artillery firing]

00:07:48.756 --> 00:07:51.919
[gunfire]

00:08:00.529 --> 00:08:03.552
Afghanistan was
the major Islamic cause

00:08:03.652 --> 00:08:06.275
in Saudi Arabia in the '80s.

00:08:06.375 --> 00:08:08.478
Americans did not want
to appear

00:08:08.578 --> 00:08:12.041
as if they are in direct war
with the Soviet Union.

00:08:12.141 --> 00:08:14.324
so we in Saudi Arabia
and Pakistan

00:08:14.424 --> 00:08:16.086
were doing a cover-up
in the operation.

00:08:16.186 --> 00:08:17.447
which was an open secret.

00:08:17.547 --> 00:08:18.969
Everybody knew about it.

00:08:19.069 --> 00:08:21.692
this Saudi-American-Pakistani
campaign

00:08:21.792 --> 00:08:24.415
to drive the Soviet Union
out of Afghanistan.

00:08:24.515 --> 00:08:27.378
♪♪♪♪♪

00:08:27.478 --> 00:08:29.701
I do not deny
that I had sympathy

00:08:29.801 --> 00:08:31.303
toward the Afghan cause.

00:08:31.403 --> 00:08:35.628
because. uh. I myself come out
from Islamic circles.

00:08:35.728 --> 00:08:38.551
and I still believe
it was a just cause.

00:08:38.651 --> 00:08:42.716
And Saudi Arabia should be
appreciated for that.

00:08:42.816 --> 00:08:46.720
And it was a big story. which.
uh. kind of. uh. made my name

00:08:46.820 --> 00:08:48.081
in the field of journalism.

00:08:48.181 --> 00:08:50.504
[all] chanting in Arabic

00:08:56.951 --> 00:08:58.493
[chanting continues]

00:08:58.593 --> 00:09:03.478
♪♪♪♪♪

00:09:05.521 --> 00:09:06.742
[Faris as Khashoggi]
The Arab News.

00:09:06.842 --> 00:09:10.226
Afghanistan.
May 4. 1988.

00:09:10.326 --> 00:09:13.169
A report by Jamal Khashoggi.

00:09:15.211 --> 00:09:16.873
Muslims are one nation.

00:09:16.973 --> 00:09:19.436
Despite geographical barriers

00:09:19.536 --> 00:09:22.520
and differences
in color and language.

00:09:22.620 --> 00:09:25.383
they consider
themselves brothers.

00:09:27.305 --> 00:09:31.970
As many as 1.000 Arab youths
are here in Afghanistan.

00:09:32.070 --> 00:09:35.454
They are actively involved
in the war.

00:09:35.554 --> 00:09:39.138
Most come
from Saudi Arabia. Egypt.

00:09:39.238 --> 00:09:41.240
Algeria. Morocco.

00:09:42.362 --> 00:09:44.784
The assistant
to the commander

00:09:44.884 --> 00:09:47.828
of the northern Panjshir base
is an Algerian

00:09:47.928 --> 00:09:50.030
named Abdullah Anas.

00:09:50.130 --> 00:09:52.353
♪♪♪♪♪

00:09:52.453 --> 00:09:54.956
[Anas] So you have
to cross seven mountains

00:09:55.056 --> 00:09:57.839
to come from Pakistan.

00:09:57.939 --> 00:10:00.602
Jamal Khashoggi.
I remember.

00:10:00.702 --> 00:10:03.045
we come across with him.

00:10:03.145 --> 00:10:05.608
You are talking
about a journey

00:10:05.708 --> 00:10:09.812
where. uh. could have.
uh. avalanche. snow.

00:10:09.912 --> 00:10:12.295
You could face air strikes.

00:10:12.395 --> 00:10:15.699
You could. uh. face ambushes
from the Soviets.

00:10:15.799 --> 00:10:18.141
But on top of being scared.

00:10:18.241 --> 00:10:19.823
you are more excited

00:10:19.923 --> 00:10:21.785
because you feel
this is a gift

00:10:21.885 --> 00:10:23.347
you are gifted by Allah.

00:10:23.447 --> 00:10:25.149
that you are part
of the mujahideen.

00:10:25.249 --> 00:10:26.871
you are. uh. um...

00:10:26.971 --> 00:10:29.634
finally. you are. uh.
making the history

00:10:29.734 --> 00:10:34.239
with these heroes and these.
uh-uh. brave people.

00:10:34.339 --> 00:10:37.122
So all this makes you
forget that threat.

00:10:37.222 --> 00:10:40.807
forget the-the fear.
forget. uh. everything.

00:10:40.907 --> 00:10:45.992
♪♪♪♪♪

00:10:47.234 --> 00:10:50.357
speaking Arabic

00:11:01.529 --> 00:11:05.074
♪♪♪♪♪

00:11:05.174 --> 00:11:07.296
[artillery firing]

00:11:09.138 --> 00:11:10.920
[Wright]
Jamal went to Afghanistan

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:13.403
to be a war correspondent.

00:11:13.503 --> 00:11:16.246
He did not have much
of a reputation then.

00:11:16.346 --> 00:11:18.248
but there was
this little group of Arabs

00:11:18.348 --> 00:11:20.531
led by Osama bin Laden.

00:11:20.631 --> 00:11:23.354
who was. at that point.
practically unknown.

00:11:24.955 --> 00:11:28.900
It was a propitious moment
in Jamal's career.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.002
They got to be friends.

00:11:33.044 --> 00:11:36.148
He was somewhat blinded

00:11:36.248 --> 00:11:38.110
by the charisma

00:11:38.210 --> 00:11:41.354
and-and the-the sense
of history

00:11:41.454 --> 00:11:43.116
that surrounded
this young man.

00:11:43.216 --> 00:11:46.279
♪♪♪♪♪

00:11:46.379 --> 00:11:49.423
[Anas] speaking Arabic

00:12:03.558 --> 00:12:05.140
[Khashoggi] I met Osama
the first time

00:12:05.240 --> 00:12:06.942
at the end of '87.

00:12:07.042 --> 00:12:09.865
and that's where I took
the first picture of him ever

00:12:09.965 --> 00:12:13.229
to be printed in any media.

00:12:13.329 --> 00:12:15.872
He was the leader or.
as he used to be called.

00:12:15.972 --> 00:12:18.795
the emir of the Arab
mujahideen in Afghanistan.

00:12:18.895 --> 00:12:20.798
[Wright] Osama bin Laden

00:12:20.898 --> 00:12:23.601
became Saudi Arabia's
first celebrity.

00:12:23.701 --> 00:12:26.404
a category that didn't exist
in Saudi Arabia

00:12:26.504 --> 00:12:28.686
until that time.
and I think. to some extent.

00:12:28.786 --> 00:12:31.389
Jamal helped him
become that person.

00:12:38.277 --> 00:12:39.618
[Bishara] Jamal and I.

00:12:39.718 --> 00:12:41.781
I mean. I was actually
an opinion page writer.

00:12:41.881 --> 00:12:44.464
so we would meet
every once in a while.

00:12:44.564 --> 00:12:46.566
uh. along with other
colleagues.

00:12:48.608 --> 00:12:51.992
Jamal was one of those
important sources.

00:12:52.092 --> 00:12:53.554
a treasure. I would say.

00:12:53.654 --> 00:12:56.317
He was sitting on this
crossroad of relationship

00:12:56.417 --> 00:12:59.320
between Saudi Arabia
and the United States

00:12:59.420 --> 00:13:02.564
fighting the Soviet Union
in Afghanistan.

00:13:02.664 --> 00:13:04.686
But of course. we would take
a lot of what he said

00:13:04.786 --> 00:13:08.290
with grain of salt
because he was. at the time.

00:13:08.390 --> 00:13:10.673
associated with
the Saudi establishment.

00:13:13.035 --> 00:13:16.700
There weren't many
Saudi or other journalists

00:13:16.800 --> 00:13:20.183
who had access to bin Laden
or to those groups.

00:13:20.283 --> 00:13:22.746
These were different times.

00:13:22.846 --> 00:13:24.789
The United States
and Saudi Arabia

00:13:24.889 --> 00:13:26.751
celebrated radical Islam

00:13:26.851 --> 00:13:28.272
as long as radical Islam

00:13:28.372 --> 00:13:31.957
was directly
against communism.

00:13:32.057 --> 00:13:34.199
[Soufan] I started working
on Osama bin Laden

00:13:34.299 --> 00:13:37.443
for the National Security
Division here in New York.

00:13:37.543 --> 00:13:39.565
I read Arabic media.

00:13:39.665 --> 00:13:42.488
and I knew of Jamal Khashoggi.

00:13:42.588 --> 00:13:45.572
and I knew about his...
you know. his-his writings

00:13:45.672 --> 00:13:47.674
and his relationship
with the Saudi government.

00:13:49.356 --> 00:13:51.418
The Saudis had a lot to gain

00:13:51.518 --> 00:13:52.900
from promoting
Osama bin Laden.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.583
and Jamal was part
of that effort.

00:13:55.683 --> 00:13:58.346
Afghan jihad made
Osama bin Laden.

00:13:58.446 --> 00:13:59.908
But the Saudis were not
doing their own thing

00:14:00.008 --> 00:14:01.349
in Afghanistan.

00:14:01.449 --> 00:14:03.592
It was a part
of the U.S.'s strategy.

00:14:03.692 --> 00:14:06.575
We gave them Stinger missiles.
for heaven's sake.

00:14:09.778 --> 00:14:11.520
The Saudis were working
very closely

00:14:11.620 --> 00:14:13.322
with the United States.

00:14:13.422 --> 00:14:15.084
They used to come and visit
Ronald Reagan

00:14:15.184 --> 00:14:16.806
in the White House.

00:14:16.906 --> 00:14:20.010
We had recruitment offices
here in the United States.

00:14:20.110 --> 00:14:21.612
[laughter]

00:14:21.712 --> 00:14:23.454
This is when
the Saudi interests.

00:14:23.554 --> 00:14:26.217
our interests.
Osama bin Laden's interests

00:14:26.317 --> 00:14:27.538
were all the same:

00:14:27.638 --> 00:14:29.861
defeat the Soviets
in Afghanistan.

00:14:29.961 --> 00:14:32.844
[applause]

00:14:34.926 --> 00:14:36.829
On behalf
of the American people.

00:14:36.929 --> 00:14:39.792
I salute Chairman Khalis.

00:14:39.892 --> 00:14:41.394
his delegation.

00:14:41.494 --> 00:14:44.477
and the people
of Afghanistan themselves.

00:14:44.577 --> 00:14:47.000
You are a nation of heroes.
God bless you.

00:14:47.100 --> 00:14:48.682
[applause]

00:14:48.782 --> 00:14:50.083
[Clarke] During
the Reagan administration.

00:14:50.183 --> 00:14:52.326
I was the Deputy Assistant
Secretary of State

00:14:52.426 --> 00:14:54.528
for Intelligence.

00:14:54.628 --> 00:14:57.451
and we were very much focused
on the war in Afghanistan

00:14:57.551 --> 00:14:59.293
on a day-to-day basis. uh.

00:14:59.393 --> 00:15:02.617
calculating how many Russian
helicopters had been shot down.

00:15:02.717 --> 00:15:03.979
They applauded.

00:15:04.079 --> 00:15:05.540
The soldiers
actually applauded.

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:06.982
[Clarke] We followed
the progress

00:15:07.082 --> 00:15:08.344
of the mujahideen

00:15:08.444 --> 00:15:11.027
in combating
the Soviet troops.

00:15:11.127 --> 00:15:14.030
and these were really
mountain people.

00:15:14.130 --> 00:15:16.593
Afghan tribal leaders.

00:15:16.693 --> 00:15:18.795
And the only thing we really
had in common with them

00:15:18.895 --> 00:15:21.398
was. we both wanted
to defeat the Soviets.

00:15:21.498 --> 00:15:23.660
We had nothing else in common.

00:15:25.462 --> 00:15:26.644
[Wright] For the U.S..

00:15:26.744 --> 00:15:28.926
spreading this kind
of radical Islam

00:15:29.026 --> 00:15:30.849
was not seen in those days
as a threat.

00:15:30.949 --> 00:15:32.010
It was just a tool.

00:15:32.110 --> 00:15:34.172
Thank you very much.

00:15:34.272 --> 00:15:37.135
[Wright] No one ever really
thought about the aftermath.

00:15:37.235 --> 00:15:39.698
[gunfire]

00:15:39.798 --> 00:15:41.540
[Rather] The retreat
of Soviet military power

00:15:41.640 --> 00:15:43.222
from Afghanistan is complete.

00:15:43.322 --> 00:15:45.865
Fear and uncertainty
were mixed with joy today

00:15:45.965 --> 00:15:48.148
as the commander
of Soviet troops

00:15:48.248 --> 00:15:50.550
followed the last of his men
across the border.

00:15:50.650 --> 00:15:53.514
leaving the communist
Afghan regime alone

00:15:53.614 --> 00:15:55.916
to face victorious
resistance fighters.

00:15:56.016 --> 00:15:58.880
♪ uneasy music ♪

00:15:58.980 --> 00:16:03.865
♪♪♪♪♪

00:16:09.471 --> 00:16:11.734
[Anas] Those days.
those years.

00:16:11.834 --> 00:16:14.377
it's the heaven of my life.

00:16:14.477 --> 00:16:16.940
I will never regret
those days.

00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:19.903
♪♪♪♪♪

00:16:20.003 --> 00:16:23.907
The mujahideen came to Kabul
in one caravan.

00:16:24.007 --> 00:16:26.670
I remember-still remember
seeing Jamal Khashoggi.

00:16:26.770 --> 00:16:28.633
"Oh. brother Abdullah."

00:16:28.733 --> 00:16:30.234
Jamal also was excited

00:16:30.334 --> 00:16:33.238
because this is the moment
he was waiting for. uh.

00:16:33.338 --> 00:16:35.340
like the hundreds
of Arabs.

00:16:36.461 --> 00:16:38.203
[Khashoggi]
I approved of the war

00:16:38.303 --> 00:16:40.646
against the Soviet Union.

00:16:40.746 --> 00:16:45.091
but in 1990 and on.
it was not the same.

00:16:45.191 --> 00:16:48.815
Al-Qaeda was established
around that time.

00:16:48.915 --> 00:16:51.458
and I covered
Osama bin Laden

00:16:51.558 --> 00:16:56.103
when he was. uh. part
of. uh. a campaign

00:16:56.203 --> 00:16:58.466
which I agreed.

00:16:58.566 --> 00:17:01.729
but I saw him change.

00:17:03.491 --> 00:17:05.954
Afghanistan had become
so ugly.

00:17:06.054 --> 00:17:08.477
Abdullah Anas. a friend.
he said to me once

00:17:08.577 --> 00:17:10.639
that he did not like it
very much.

00:17:10.739 --> 00:17:11.961
It was full of divisions.

00:17:12.061 --> 00:17:15.485
full of envy
and poisonous ideas.

00:17:15.585 --> 00:17:17.587
I think he was right.

00:17:18.388 --> 00:17:22.853
This happiness slowly.
slowly started to-to transfer

00:17:22.953 --> 00:17:24.294
to a nightmare.

00:17:24.394 --> 00:17:26.817
to a funeral.

00:17:26.917 --> 00:17:31.442
and then the rockets started
coming from everywhere.

00:17:33.124 --> 00:17:35.507
So all that dream. gone.

00:17:35.607 --> 00:17:39.191
Replaced by civil war.

00:17:39.291 --> 00:17:41.153
♪ somber music ♪

00:17:41.253 --> 00:17:45.118
[Clarke] If we had
just left Afghanistan alone.

00:17:45.218 --> 00:17:47.320
in 20/20 hindsight.

00:17:47.420 --> 00:17:50.323
I think things might have been
better. uh. in the long run.

00:17:50.423 --> 00:17:52.766
♪♪♪♪♪

00:17:52.866 --> 00:17:54.568
[Brennan]
Both within CIA

00:17:54.668 --> 00:17:56.130
as well as in
the Saudi government.

00:17:56.230 --> 00:17:59.133
there was a sense
of accomplishment.

00:17:59.233 --> 00:18:02.697
There were certainly missteps
that had consequences.

00:18:02.797 --> 00:18:04.299
uh. negative consequences.
whatever.

00:18:04.399 --> 00:18:06.581
but. uh. that's history.

00:18:06.681 --> 00:18:08.303
♪♪♪♪♪

00:18:08.403 --> 00:18:10.526
[jet engine whooshing]

00:18:13.649 --> 00:18:16.733
[crowd screaming]

00:18:18.655 --> 00:18:21.778
[sirens wailing]

00:18:25.182 --> 00:18:27.184
[horns blaring]

00:18:30.348 --> 00:18:33.631
[panicked chatter]

00:18:36.074 --> 00:18:39.638
[sirens blaring]

00:18:40.479 --> 00:18:43.482
[Faris as Khashoggi] I
collapsed crying a while ago.

00:18:44.323 --> 00:18:48.047
Why did 15 of our young men
take part in the attacks?

00:18:50.370 --> 00:18:52.893
What can we tell
these boys' mothers?

00:18:54.454 --> 00:18:58.219
Will we repeat the lie that
they were martyred for Islam?

00:19:01.182 --> 00:19:03.885
I collapsed crying
a while ago.

00:19:03.985 --> 00:19:07.449
heartbroken for you. Osama.

00:19:07.549 --> 00:19:09.131
You were beautiful and brave

00:19:09.231 --> 00:19:13.295
in those beautiful days
in Afghanistan

00:19:13.395 --> 00:19:16.999
before you surrendered
to hatred and rage.

00:19:19.883 --> 00:19:22.566
What happened
in the last ten years?

00:19:27.011 --> 00:19:29.033
We must ensure
that our children

00:19:29.133 --> 00:19:32.797
can never be influenced
by extremist ideas.

00:19:32.897 --> 00:19:34.959
like those 15 Saudis

00:19:35.059 --> 00:19:37.843
who were misled
into hijacking four planes

00:19:37.943 --> 00:19:41.206
that fine September day.

00:19:41.306 --> 00:19:43.929
piloting them and us

00:19:44.029 --> 00:19:48.294
straight into
the jaws of hell.

00:19:48.394 --> 00:19:53.560
♪♪♪♪♪

00:19:56.683 --> 00:19:58.626
[Clarke]
A lot of us felt rage.

00:19:58.726 --> 00:20:00.388
rage against
our own government

00:20:00.488 --> 00:20:02.190
that we were part of.

00:20:02.290 --> 00:20:04.913
Fifteen of the hijackers
were Saudis.

00:20:05.013 --> 00:20:07.195
and the warnings were clear.

00:20:07.295 --> 00:20:10.199
but they were ignored
at the highest levels.

00:20:10.299 --> 00:20:11.680
uh. repeatedly.

00:20:11.780 --> 00:20:12.841
and the price was enormous.

00:20:12.941 --> 00:20:16.325
[indistinct chatter]

00:20:16.425 --> 00:20:18.428
[gavel banging]

00:20:23.433 --> 00:20:25.976
[Kean] Our next witness
is Mr. Richard Clarke.

00:20:26.076 --> 00:20:28.098
who served as a former
National Coordinator

00:20:28.198 --> 00:20:30.982
for Counterterrorism at
the National Security Council.

00:20:31.082 --> 00:20:32.904
[Clarke] I think
the Saudi government knew

00:20:33.004 --> 00:20:35.467
that they were at risk
of the American people

00:20:35.567 --> 00:20:38.550
and the American Congress
and the American media

00:20:38.650 --> 00:20:42.194
going after them. uh. for
having supported. uh. al-Qaeda.

00:20:42.294 --> 00:20:46.879
To the loved ones
of the victims of 9/11.

00:20:46.979 --> 00:20:49.522
to them who are here
in the room.

00:20:49.622 --> 00:20:53.447
to those who are watching
on television.

00:20:53.547 --> 00:20:56.890
your government failed you.

00:20:56.990 --> 00:21:01.776
Those entrusted with
protecting you failed you.

00:21:01.876 --> 00:21:04.939
And I failed you.

00:21:05.039 --> 00:21:07.222
[Rhodes] I worked two years
for the Democratic

00:21:07.322 --> 00:21:09.785
Vice Chairman
of the 9/11 Commission.

00:21:09.885 --> 00:21:12.388
and one of the areas
of research that I did for him

00:21:12.488 --> 00:21:14.750
was Saudi Arabia. and...

00:21:14.850 --> 00:21:18.514
and. um. you know.

00:21:18.614 --> 00:21:20.917
as someone who witnessed 9/11.
who's a New Yorker.

00:21:21.017 --> 00:21:22.439
it wasn't just the reality

00:21:22.539 --> 00:21:25.722
that 15 of the 19 hijackers
were Saudi

00:21:25.822 --> 00:21:28.445
but also that a lot
of the financing for al-Qaeda

00:21:28.545 --> 00:21:30.928
came from wealthy
Saudi individuals.

00:21:31.028 --> 00:21:33.171
[indistinct chatter]

00:21:33.271 --> 00:21:35.774
[Rundell] You gotta remember
that the 3.000 dead Americans

00:21:35.874 --> 00:21:37.135
were not the result
of anything

00:21:37.235 --> 00:21:39.257
that the Saudi government did.

00:21:39.357 --> 00:21:41.860
You could argue
that by supporting

00:21:41.960 --> 00:21:43.782
the mujahideen
in the first place.

00:21:43.882 --> 00:21:46.986
they had encouraged
this idea of jihad.

00:21:47.086 --> 00:21:48.908
and I think
that's-that's fair enough.

00:21:49.008 --> 00:21:49.949
So had we.

00:21:50.049 --> 00:21:52.913
♪♪♪♪♪

00:21:53.013 --> 00:21:55.275
[Wright] I don't know
if Jamal had regrets

00:21:55.375 --> 00:21:57.758
about his past life.

00:21:57.858 --> 00:22:00.020
He did evolve
away from things.

00:22:01.902 --> 00:22:04.445
Jamal looked at bin Laden
with stars in his eyes

00:22:04.545 --> 00:22:08.850
when he was young. and then
he became disillusioned.

00:22:08.950 --> 00:22:12.775
He began to hate what
bin Laden had become and...

00:22:12.875 --> 00:22:16.819
you know. and what he had done
to Saudi society and to Islam.

00:22:16.919 --> 00:22:19.822
So he became
a Saudi defender

00:22:19.922 --> 00:22:22.305
and a supporter
of the royal family.

00:22:22.405 --> 00:22:23.667
[phone rings]

00:22:23.767 --> 00:22:26.370
♪ tense music ♪

00:22:28.972 --> 00:22:31.375
[bin Laden] speaking Arabic

00:22:40.185 --> 00:22:43.228
[Anas] speaking Arabic

00:23:08.977 --> 00:23:11.440
[Salem]
Jamal was a loyal Saudi.

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:15.524
And I think how he defined
that loyalty over time

00:23:15.624 --> 00:23:17.887
clearly evolved and changed.

00:23:17.987 --> 00:23:20.009
as did the kingdom itself.

00:23:20.109 --> 00:23:24.314
He may have seen it
as the least bad option.

00:23:26.316 --> 00:23:27.938
I met Jamal
when I was working

00:23:28.038 --> 00:23:29.820
at the Middle East Institute.

00:23:29.920 --> 00:23:31.902
He was like a big teddy bear.

00:23:32.002 --> 00:23:33.905
There was just a genuineness.

00:23:34.005 --> 00:23:37.549
Always a smile.
even in the worst of times.

00:23:37.649 --> 00:23:40.672
He. in many ways.
was like a big brother to me.

00:23:40.772 --> 00:23:42.594
That was our relationship.

00:23:42.694 --> 00:23:44.196
[all] speaking Arabic

00:23:44.296 --> 00:23:47.280
[Salem] At the time.
he worked for the al-Faisals.

00:23:47.380 --> 00:23:50.003
who were seen as sort of
the intelligentsia

00:23:50.103 --> 00:23:52.425
of the royal family.

00:23:53.346 --> 00:23:55.328
[Brennan] The Saudis
were rather reluctant partners

00:23:55.428 --> 00:23:56.930
after 9/11.

00:23:57.030 --> 00:23:59.253
but Turki al-Faisal
was well-known

00:23:59.353 --> 00:24:01.015
for believing strongly
in the importance

00:24:01.115 --> 00:24:03.177
of a U.S.-Saudi relationship.

00:24:03.277 --> 00:24:06.741
He was my counterpart
in Saudi Arabia in the '90s.

00:24:06.841 --> 00:24:08.583
King Fahd was ill and infirm

00:24:08.683 --> 00:24:11.146
and not in day-to-day charge
of the government.

00:24:11.246 --> 00:24:13.589
and so Turki was determined
to make sure

00:24:13.689 --> 00:24:15.991
that that relationship
between Riyadh and Washington

00:24:16.091 --> 00:24:18.674
was going to not just
remain strong

00:24:18.774 --> 00:24:20.316
but in fact be strengthened.

00:24:20.416 --> 00:24:23.860
[applause]

00:24:25.422 --> 00:24:27.925
There are those
who would have you believe

00:24:28.025 --> 00:24:30.728
that the current wave
of terrorism

00:24:30.828 --> 00:24:34.212
springs from
and is or has been

00:24:34.312 --> 00:24:36.594
supported by Saudi Arabia.

00:24:38.076 --> 00:24:40.138
That is absolutely not true.

00:24:40.238 --> 00:24:41.980
[Brennan] After 9/11.
Prince Turki

00:24:42.080 --> 00:24:44.343
became Saudi ambassador
to London.

00:24:44.443 --> 00:24:46.746
Jamal was somebody
who had a good reputation

00:24:46.846 --> 00:24:49.388
in the international media.
and I think Turki thought

00:24:49.488 --> 00:24:52.792
that Jamal's voice
would be a useful one

00:24:52.892 --> 00:24:54.194
in trying to battle

00:24:54.294 --> 00:24:58.278
this very broad misimpression

00:24:58.378 --> 00:25:00.120
of Saudi Arabia as a whole.

00:25:00.220 --> 00:25:03.644
[train whistle blows]

00:25:03.744 --> 00:25:06.648
♪ gentle music ♪

00:25:06.748 --> 00:25:09.771
♪♪♪♪♪

00:25:09.871 --> 00:25:13.335
[Wright] I went to London
and I met with Turki.

00:25:13.435 --> 00:25:16.458
and I spent a lot of time
with Jamal there.

00:25:16.558 --> 00:25:20.223
He seemed to be
enjoying London.

00:25:20.323 --> 00:25:24.027
When you are the spokesperson
for a senior prince.

00:25:24.127 --> 00:25:26.129
you're untouchable.

00:25:27.851 --> 00:25:29.673
Jamal was useful to Turki

00:25:29.773 --> 00:25:33.377
because he had credibility
among reporters. like me.

00:25:35.299 --> 00:25:37.202
[Obaid] Jamal and I
worked very closely.

00:25:37.302 --> 00:25:40.165
first in London
and then in D.C.

00:25:40.265 --> 00:25:42.207
He was older than me.

00:25:42.307 --> 00:25:43.649
and so the joke
within the embassy

00:25:43.749 --> 00:25:44.850
and within our friends

00:25:44.950 --> 00:25:47.173
was that I would call him
Uncle J.

00:25:47.273 --> 00:25:49.775
We became quite close.

00:25:49.875 --> 00:25:51.537
Mornings would start at 7:30.

00:25:51.637 --> 00:25:54.140
We'd be the first one
at the embassy.

00:25:54.240 --> 00:25:57.224
After work. we would
usually go have teas.

00:25:57.324 --> 00:26:00.668
And in a way. work never
ended at the embassy.

00:26:00.768 --> 00:26:02.670
He was always the nice guy
and I was the bad guy.

00:26:02.770 --> 00:26:05.473
I was always giving
a hard time to the press.

00:26:05.573 --> 00:26:08.276
and it was crisis
after crisis after crisis.

00:26:08.376 --> 00:26:10.238
On the contrary. the Saudis
actually have done

00:26:10.338 --> 00:26:11.920
a lot behind the scenes.

00:26:12.020 --> 00:26:13.121
but more importantly.

00:26:13.221 --> 00:26:15.244
you talked about
the American media.

00:26:15.344 --> 00:26:16.846
They've been the-they've been
the people

00:26:16.946 --> 00:26:18.047
that have been
raising the issue.

00:26:18.147 --> 00:26:20.049
The U.S. administration.
the Bush administration

00:26:20.149 --> 00:26:21.651
has not at all.

00:26:21.751 --> 00:26:22.892
It was very raw.

00:26:22.992 --> 00:26:24.814
America was very upset.

00:26:24.914 --> 00:26:28.178
We spent a lot of our time
defending the Saudi position

00:26:28.278 --> 00:26:30.260
vis-à-vis the attacks
of 9/11.

00:26:30.360 --> 00:26:32.022
The U.S. cannot go
accusing people

00:26:32.122 --> 00:26:35.306
of financing. uh. terrorism
by merely--

00:26:35.406 --> 00:26:40.111
[indistinct] by merely
unfounded intelligence reports.

00:26:40.211 --> 00:26:42.594
[Obaid] You had
a Bush administration

00:26:42.694 --> 00:26:45.918
that was still very close
to Saudi Arabia.

00:26:46.018 --> 00:26:47.279
Somebody asked me
the other day.

00:26:47.379 --> 00:26:48.721
was I pleased with the actions
of Saudi Arabia?

00:26:48.821 --> 00:26:49.962
I am.

00:26:50.062 --> 00:26:51.484
[Obaid]
And that was important.

00:26:51.584 --> 00:26:53.927
because without that.
the U.S.-Saudi relationship

00:26:54.027 --> 00:26:54.928
could not have continued.

00:26:55.028 --> 00:26:59.513
♪♪♪♪♪

00:27:04.719 --> 00:27:07.221
It's up to us
to bankrupt the terrorists

00:27:07.321 --> 00:27:09.664
and those who finance them
so they will never again

00:27:09.764 --> 00:27:12.828
have the resources
to commit such atrocities

00:27:12.928 --> 00:27:14.109
against the American people

00:27:14.209 --> 00:27:16.712
as we experienced
on September 11th.

00:27:16.812 --> 00:27:18.514
[Maloney]
The 9/11 families believe.

00:27:18.614 --> 00:27:20.676
and we've alleged formally
in a complaint

00:27:20.776 --> 00:27:21.718
filed in federal court.

00:27:21.818 --> 00:27:23.960
that members
of the Saudi government

00:27:24.060 --> 00:27:25.642
conspired with al-Qaeda

00:27:25.742 --> 00:27:27.884
for more than a decade
in funding them.

00:27:27.984 --> 00:27:30.647
financing them.
providing logistical support.

00:27:30.747 --> 00:27:34.211
and other means and methods
to keep them going.

00:27:34.311 --> 00:27:36.254
What we hear
from American officials.

00:27:36.354 --> 00:27:37.655
they are happy
with the cooperation.

00:27:37.755 --> 00:27:39.177
They are happy
with the information

00:27:39.277 --> 00:27:40.338
they are getting
from the Saudis.

00:27:40.438 --> 00:27:41.820
They are getting
plenty of information

00:27:41.920 --> 00:27:44.543
about the case
of the 15 hijackers.

00:27:44.643 --> 00:27:47.386
[Clarke] How did money move
to bin Laden?

00:27:47.486 --> 00:27:49.588
Did it move
through Saudi banks?

00:27:49.688 --> 00:27:51.711
Were there wealthy
Saudi individuals

00:27:51.811 --> 00:27:52.872
who were funding him?

00:27:52.972 --> 00:27:54.634
There was a lot
of cooperation

00:27:54.734 --> 00:27:56.676
that we wanted
out of the Saudi government

00:27:56.776 --> 00:27:58.759
that we did not get.

00:27:58.859 --> 00:28:01.842
[Maloney] Our own government
withheld a lot of material

00:28:01.942 --> 00:28:05.306
to prevent us
from embarrassing the Saudis.

00:28:07.348 --> 00:28:09.531
There's obviously a lot
of political influence

00:28:09.631 --> 00:28:12.214
the Saudis still enjoy
in Washington. D.C..

00:28:12.314 --> 00:28:14.656
and they made
their best efforts

00:28:14.756 --> 00:28:17.019
to prevent this lawsuit from
ever seeing the light of day.

00:28:17.119 --> 00:28:19.702
♪♪♪♪♪

00:28:19.802 --> 00:28:21.744
[Soufan] I don't call
Saudi Arabia an ally.

00:28:21.844 --> 00:28:24.427
I never called
Saudi Arabia an ally.

00:28:24.527 --> 00:28:27.791
They always look to cover up
what they don't want

00:28:27.891 --> 00:28:29.833
the outside world to know

00:28:29.933 --> 00:28:32.036
about events and activities

00:28:32.136 --> 00:28:33.998
and networks
inside the kingdom.

00:28:34.098 --> 00:28:36.961
♪♪♪♪♪

00:28:37.061 --> 00:28:39.083
[Clarke] You have to remember.
this was a government

00:28:39.183 --> 00:28:42.848
that was very sympathetic
to the Saudi royal family.

00:28:42.948 --> 00:28:46.552
And the Bush family had ties
going back for decades.

00:28:48.073 --> 00:28:49.535
I think the Bush
administration's

00:28:49.635 --> 00:28:52.859
number one goal
after 9/11 was Iraq.

00:28:52.959 --> 00:28:55.702
They sat down
the first week after 9/11

00:28:55.802 --> 00:28:58.265
and said. "Shall we go
into Afghanistan first?

00:28:58.365 --> 00:29:01.308
Or shall we go
into Iraq first?"

00:29:01.408 --> 00:29:03.310
I felt like a man from Mars.

00:29:03.410 --> 00:29:08.076
and I said to them.
"Invading Iraq after 9/11

00:29:08.176 --> 00:29:10.118
would be like
if Franklin Roosevelt.

00:29:10.218 --> 00:29:12.761
after Pearl Harbor. had said.

00:29:12.861 --> 00:29:15.043
'Let's invade Mexico.'"

00:29:15.143 --> 00:29:18.287
I didn't understand how these
very rational senior people

00:29:18.387 --> 00:29:20.449
had lost their mind.

00:29:20.549 --> 00:29:22.492
and I don't think
the Bush administration

00:29:22.592 --> 00:29:25.455
could have fought the Iraq War
without Saudi support.

00:29:25.555 --> 00:29:28.258
[indistinct chatter]

00:29:28.358 --> 00:29:29.619
[Bishara]
I think Saudi Arabia

00:29:29.719 --> 00:29:32.142
became even more
indispensable

00:29:32.242 --> 00:29:34.625
for the United States.

00:29:34.725 --> 00:29:36.908
Jamal Khashoggi
and Turki al-Faisal.

00:29:37.008 --> 00:29:41.473
they were champions
of Saudi-American relations.

00:29:41.573 --> 00:29:44.316
Never defended it.
Never justified it.

00:29:44.416 --> 00:29:46.638
They were champions of it.

00:29:46.738 --> 00:29:49.241
[Wright] Jamal
was the only Arab I met

00:29:49.341 --> 00:29:52.445
who was a supporter
of the war.

00:29:52.545 --> 00:29:55.929
By the time
the U.S. invaded Iraq.

00:29:56.029 --> 00:29:57.130
he struck me as a neocon.

00:29:57.230 --> 00:29:58.692
He was all in favor of it.

00:29:58.792 --> 00:30:00.794
speaking Arabic

00:30:12.807 --> 00:30:14.750
[Obaid]
He was nationalistic.

00:30:14.850 --> 00:30:16.992
He felt very much
involved in it.

00:30:17.092 --> 00:30:19.835
and so. you know.
it's times change.

00:30:19.935 --> 00:30:23.539
but a lot of people
don't know that side of Jamal.

00:30:24.700 --> 00:30:26.703
Jamal took it very personally.

00:30:28.064 --> 00:30:30.167
Some of the papers.
including The New York Times.

00:30:30.267 --> 00:30:31.889
insist on calling him
a dissident.

00:30:31.989 --> 00:30:33.771
Jamal was...

00:30:33.871 --> 00:30:34.852
[Bradley] You've
arrested reformers

00:30:34.952 --> 00:30:36.293
by the hundreds
and the thousands.

00:30:36.393 --> 00:30:37.535
No. no. no. reformers.
they were never

00:30:37.635 --> 00:30:38.936
arrested by the. uh--

00:30:39.036 --> 00:30:41.019
Peaceful demonstrators
who went into the street.

00:30:41.119 --> 00:30:44.182
there were many hundreds
of them arrested in Riyadh--

00:30:44.282 --> 00:30:46.184
The demonstrators...
those demonstrators

00:30:46.284 --> 00:30:49.828
were ans-they were answering
a call of an al-Qaeda activist.

00:30:49.928 --> 00:30:52.351
They were answering the call
of Sa'ad Al-Faqih.

00:30:52.451 --> 00:30:54.193
They were not
peaceful demonstrators.

00:30:54.293 --> 00:30:56.436
[Bradley] They were holding
Korans above their head.

00:30:56.536 --> 00:30:57.757
and they were
peaceful demonstrators.

00:30:57.857 --> 00:30:59.079
- They were unarmed.
- But again.

00:30:59.179 --> 00:31:01.081
there were no shooting;
they were released.

00:31:01.181 --> 00:31:02.402
[Bradley]
There was shooting.

00:31:02.502 --> 00:31:04.244
They shot rubber bullets
over their heads.

00:31:04.344 --> 00:31:06.367
The-uh. nobody was killed.

00:31:06.467 --> 00:31:08.729
Uh. they were all released.

00:31:08.829 --> 00:31:11.493
We don't have
this situation where we...

00:31:11.593 --> 00:31:14.576
where people demonstrate
in the streets and chaos.

00:31:14.676 --> 00:31:16.378
No. we don't have
any-any of that.

00:31:16.478 --> 00:31:17.539
Saudi Arabia is very stable.

00:31:17.639 --> 00:31:20.543
♪ tense music ♪

00:31:20.643 --> 00:31:25.528
♪♪♪♪♪

00:31:27.050 --> 00:31:29.432
[Faris as Khashoggi] A country
as proud as Saudi Arabia

00:31:29.532 --> 00:31:32.596
doesn't take easily
to outside advice.

00:31:32.696 --> 00:31:34.959
Yet just because 15 Saudis

00:31:35.059 --> 00:31:38.362
committed the biggest
terrorist atrocity in history.

00:31:38.462 --> 00:31:40.685
some Americans are now calling

00:31:40.785 --> 00:31:43.008
for the imposition
of a foreign culture

00:31:43.108 --> 00:31:45.530
on our Muslim society.

00:31:45.630 --> 00:31:48.353
That is why we have
to fight back.

00:31:49.795 --> 00:31:52.178
Last November.
Prince Turki al-Faisal

00:31:52.278 --> 00:31:54.460
won a legal battle
against the families

00:31:54.560 --> 00:31:56.663
of September 11th victims.

00:31:56.763 --> 00:31:58.765
This was good news.

00:32:00.046 --> 00:32:01.108
The Bush administration

00:32:01.208 --> 00:32:03.851
still considers Saudi Arabia
a friend.

00:32:05.893 --> 00:32:08.936
But we do not know
what the future holds.

00:32:10.778 --> 00:32:14.522
[Bishara] Jamal's 30 years
in Arab media

00:32:14.622 --> 00:32:17.686
reflect Saudi relations
with the United States

00:32:17.786 --> 00:32:20.449
and Arab public opinion.

00:32:20.549 --> 00:32:24.694
He championed the cause
for American-Saudi cooperation

00:32:24.794 --> 00:32:27.937
against the Soviet Union
in Afghanistan.

00:32:28.037 --> 00:32:30.540
After 9/11. they worked
with the United States

00:32:30.640 --> 00:32:32.462
against Saddam Hussein
of Iraq

00:32:32.562 --> 00:32:35.506
and supported
the U.S. war on terror.

00:32:35.606 --> 00:32:38.149
At each and every junction

00:32:38.249 --> 00:32:40.992
in modern Saudi history

00:32:41.092 --> 00:32:44.276
and modern
U.S.-Saudi relations.

00:32:44.376 --> 00:32:46.999
Jamal was there
at that crossroad.

00:32:47.099 --> 00:32:51.063
either reporting.
explaining. or spinning.

00:32:52.064 --> 00:32:55.588
But he was taken by surprise
by the Arab Spring.

00:32:57.870 --> 00:33:00.914
[crowd] chanting in Arabic

00:33:08.242 --> 00:33:11.706
[Bishara] The Arab Spring
was indeed a revolution

00:33:11.806 --> 00:33:14.389
that shook Saudi Arabia.

00:33:14.489 --> 00:33:17.192
It was like an earthquake.

00:33:17.292 --> 00:33:20.596
In the past. you could always
count on the United States.

00:33:20.696 --> 00:33:23.279
But when it came
to the Arab Spring.

00:33:23.379 --> 00:33:25.762
they could not find help
in Washington.

00:33:25.862 --> 00:33:27.323
[all] chanting in Arabic

00:33:27.423 --> 00:33:28.885
[Bishara]
That was unprecedented.

00:33:28.985 --> 00:33:31.768
that was unthinkable.
and it was so sudden.

00:33:31.868 --> 00:33:33.870
[all] chanting in Arabic

00:33:36.754 --> 00:33:39.477
[Karman] speaking Arabic

00:33:57.897 --> 00:33:59.599
[man] speaking Arabic

00:33:59.699 --> 00:34:02.322
[Soltan]
It felt like coming home.

00:34:02.422 --> 00:34:04.445
Seeing young Arabs

00:34:04.545 --> 00:34:06.607
take to the streets

00:34:06.707 --> 00:34:09.410
to realize that dream

00:34:09.510 --> 00:34:11.332
for self-determination.

00:34:11.432 --> 00:34:14.095
for liberty. freedom.

00:34:14.195 --> 00:34:16.458
bread. social justice

00:34:16.558 --> 00:34:18.540
was my dream coming true.

00:34:18.640 --> 00:34:20.642
and I couldn't
not take part in it.

00:34:47.833 --> 00:34:49.695
[all] chanting in Arabic

00:34:49.795 --> 00:34:52.658
♪ light dramatic music ♪

00:34:52.758 --> 00:34:55.982
♪♪♪♪♪

00:34:56.082 --> 00:34:57.864
[Obaid] When the Arab Spring
kicked off.

00:34:57.964 --> 00:35:00.907
that was kind of our first
open disagreement.

00:35:01.007 --> 00:35:02.989
He was for what happened
in other countries.

00:35:03.089 --> 00:35:04.791
and I was against it.

00:35:04.891 --> 00:35:06.794
It called it
"the so-called Arab Spring."

00:35:06.894 --> 00:35:09.397
because what does that mean
for other countries

00:35:09.497 --> 00:35:12.240
of which Saudi Arabia
is an ally and a supporter?

00:35:12.340 --> 00:35:15.483
♪ dramatic music ♪

00:35:15.583 --> 00:35:17.325
♪♪♪♪♪

00:35:17.425 --> 00:35:19.007
[Brennan] At the time
of the Arab Spring.

00:35:19.107 --> 00:35:23.412
King Abdullah was viewed
as being somewhat skeptical

00:35:23.512 --> 00:35:26.335
of that
U.S.-Saudi relationship.

00:35:26.435 --> 00:35:29.379
He didn't support everything
that the United States did

00:35:29.479 --> 00:35:31.101
in the region.
and I think there were people

00:35:31.201 --> 00:35:33.023
who came in with
the Obama administration

00:35:33.123 --> 00:35:35.706
who had. oh. I think.
a rather jaundiced view.

00:35:35.806 --> 00:35:36.907
uh. of Saudi Arabia.

00:35:37.007 --> 00:35:38.869
There were problems
with the fact

00:35:38.969 --> 00:35:40.351
that these governments

00:35:40.451 --> 00:35:42.914
kind of couldn't keep a lid
on things anymore.

00:35:43.014 --> 00:35:46.197
I was in a group of advisors

00:35:46.297 --> 00:35:48.880
who were urging
President Obama

00:35:48.980 --> 00:35:52.264
to try to support
a transition to democracy.

00:35:53.666 --> 00:35:55.247
King Abdullah
of Saudi Arabia

00:35:55.347 --> 00:35:57.690
wanted to talk to Obama.

00:35:57.790 --> 00:35:59.532
and I remember
in that phone call

00:35:59.632 --> 00:36:03.256
King Abdullah was absolutely
livid about this.

00:36:03.356 --> 00:36:06.340
and his basic line was.

00:36:06.440 --> 00:36:08.422
everybody in that square

00:36:08.522 --> 00:36:11.085
is either a terrorist
or an Iranian agent.

00:36:12.286 --> 00:36:15.670
Which was just
patently not true.

00:36:15.770 --> 00:36:18.714
And President Obama
called Mubarak and told him.

00:36:18.814 --> 00:36:20.075
"Look. I think
you need to step down.

00:36:20.175 --> 00:36:21.757
I don't think these protests
are going to stop."

00:36:21.857 --> 00:36:24.160
[all] shouting in Arabic

00:36:24.260 --> 00:36:27.043
[Soltan] We were
at the presidential palace.

00:36:27.143 --> 00:36:29.846
We told the army generals

00:36:29.946 --> 00:36:33.089
that after this prayer.

00:36:33.189 --> 00:36:37.254
we were going to break through
and storm the palace.

00:36:37.354 --> 00:36:39.096
We said. "If you open fire
on the front line.

00:36:39.196 --> 00:36:40.698
there's 50.000 people
behind us.

00:36:40.798 --> 00:36:42.580
We're getting in regardless."

00:36:42.680 --> 00:36:45.063
I remember crying my eyes out
because I felt like

00:36:45.163 --> 00:36:46.625
this could be my last prayer.

00:36:46.725 --> 00:36:49.307
that if they opened fire.
you know. this was worth it.

00:36:49.407 --> 00:36:52.471
[crowd shouting]

00:36:52.571 --> 00:36:54.994
[Soltan] We hear the
announcement on the P.A.

00:36:55.094 --> 00:36:57.857
[man over P.A. system]
speaking Arabic

00:37:10.711 --> 00:37:13.134
[crowd cheering wildly]

00:37:13.234 --> 00:37:16.538
♪ uplifting music ♪

00:37:16.638 --> 00:37:19.901
[all] chanting in Arabic

00:37:20.001 --> 00:37:24.727
♪♪♪♪♪

00:37:38.782 --> 00:37:42.086
[Soltan]
It was the best of Egypt.

00:37:42.186 --> 00:37:44.889
And it was the best of
the Arab world at that time.

00:37:44.989 --> 00:37:47.452
best 18 days
of our generation.

00:37:47.552 --> 00:37:50.756
- [crowd cheering]
- [fireworks popping]

00:37:51.556 --> 00:37:53.979
It was...

00:37:54.079 --> 00:37:55.381
one hell of a time.

00:37:55.481 --> 00:37:57.483
[laughs]

00:37:58.885 --> 00:38:01.788
♪ gentle music ♪

00:38:01.888 --> 00:38:04.511
♪♪♪♪♪

00:38:04.611 --> 00:38:07.554
[Faris as Khashoggi]
Egyptians did not need anyone

00:38:07.654 --> 00:38:10.157
to teach them how to be free.

00:38:10.257 --> 00:38:13.441
I saw them take to it

00:38:13.541 --> 00:38:16.364
like a human instinct.

00:38:16.464 --> 00:38:19.047
At the time. I was living
a new love story

00:38:19.147 --> 00:38:21.290
and a new marriage.

00:38:21.390 --> 00:38:26.095
Egypt was also living
its love story with freedom.

00:38:26.195 --> 00:38:30.460
It was the happiest time
for both of us.

00:38:30.560 --> 00:38:32.742
[Salem] Jamal was
a big romantic.

00:38:32.842 --> 00:38:35.545
In every sense. a romantic.

00:38:35.645 --> 00:38:37.808
You get swept up in it.

00:38:39.329 --> 00:38:42.874
Jamal loved strong.
intelligent women.

00:38:42.974 --> 00:38:45.837
and at the start
of the Arab Spring.

00:38:45.937 --> 00:38:50.001
he'd married a really
wonderful woman. Dr. Alaa.

00:38:50.101 --> 00:38:53.325
♪♪♪♪♪

00:38:53.425 --> 00:38:58.090
And there is a certain romance
to revolutions.

00:38:58.190 --> 00:39:01.895
to the idea
that you can throw off

00:39:01.995 --> 00:39:04.017
the restrictions

00:39:04.117 --> 00:39:07.221
that seemed impossible
to shake

00:39:07.321 --> 00:39:11.025
and that you could think
and discuss ideas

00:39:11.125 --> 00:39:14.429
that were forbidden before.

00:39:14.529 --> 00:39:18.753
and that...that oxygen.
I think. is intoxicating.

00:39:18.853 --> 00:39:22.357
♪♪♪♪♪

00:39:22.457 --> 00:39:24.960
[Obaid] Jamal was very open
about how happy he was

00:39:25.060 --> 00:39:27.103
that Mubarak had gone down.

00:39:28.224 --> 00:39:30.126
But he made a lot of enemies

00:39:30.226 --> 00:39:32.929
because of his writing
and his tweets.

00:39:33.029 --> 00:39:34.931
and I kept telling Jamal.
"Stop.

00:39:35.031 --> 00:39:36.293
You know. stop."

00:39:36.393 --> 00:39:38.295
We had a lot of arguments
about it.

00:39:38.395 --> 00:39:40.217
King Abdullah kept
getting angry at him.

00:39:40.317 --> 00:39:42.139
told him. you know.
"What you're writing.

00:39:42.239 --> 00:39:44.302
you know. relax."

00:39:44.402 --> 00:39:47.465
There was a sense
of a lot of worry.

00:39:47.565 --> 00:39:51.149
I would say the relationship
Saudi Arabia had with America

00:39:51.249 --> 00:39:53.392
started being very testy.

00:39:53.492 --> 00:39:55.554
The Saudis believed.

00:39:55.654 --> 00:39:58.998
uh. that we let Mubarak down.

00:39:59.098 --> 00:40:00.600
um. that he had been

00:40:00.700 --> 00:40:02.442
a very loyal ally
for 30 years.

00:40:02.542 --> 00:40:05.325
that he had done what we
asked him to do many times.

00:40:05.425 --> 00:40:08.088
and that at the first sign
of trouble.

00:40:08.188 --> 00:40:09.610
uh. we threw him under the bus.

00:40:09.710 --> 00:40:13.094
[all] chanting in Arabic

00:40:13.194 --> 00:40:16.537
Saudi Arabia was paying
people to protest.

00:40:16.637 --> 00:40:19.541
[all] chanting in Arabic

00:40:19.641 --> 00:40:21.423
[Rhodes] And ultimately.
this results

00:40:21.523 --> 00:40:23.465
in the Egyptian military
overthrowing

00:40:23.565 --> 00:40:25.307
a democratically elected
government

00:40:25.407 --> 00:40:26.989
with the backing
of Saudi Arabia.

00:40:27.089 --> 00:40:28.511
They funded it.

00:40:28.611 --> 00:40:31.354
They drove the media strategy
behind it.

00:40:31.454 --> 00:40:34.157
[Brennan] Saudi Arabia
and others were concerned

00:40:34.257 --> 00:40:36.520
that the Arab Spring
was going to.

00:40:36.620 --> 00:40:37.761
uh. go out of control.

00:40:37.861 --> 00:40:39.323
Nobody wanted that.

00:40:39.423 --> 00:40:41.285
United States didn't want that.
Saudi Arabia didn't want that.

00:40:41.385 --> 00:40:42.727
[man] It was reported
that Egypt's

00:40:42.827 --> 00:40:45.369
first democratically
elected president

00:40:45.469 --> 00:40:47.572
was no longer allowed
to leave the country

00:40:47.672 --> 00:40:49.294
and that the army
was deploying

00:40:49.394 --> 00:40:51.576
not just here
but on the streets.

00:40:51.676 --> 00:40:54.620
♪ dark music ♪

00:40:54.720 --> 00:40:56.862
[Rhodes] President Obama.
at this point.

00:40:56.962 --> 00:40:59.185
is kind of worn down by this.

00:40:59.285 --> 00:41:02.148
and we never followed through
on a policy

00:41:02.248 --> 00:41:04.250
that really prioritized
democracy promotion.

00:41:05.532 --> 00:41:07.314
Not only was that
kind of the death knell

00:41:07.414 --> 00:41:10.878
of the Arab Spring.
but it was also kind of.

00:41:10.978 --> 00:41:13.000
to me.
like a pretty cynical.

00:41:13.100 --> 00:41:15.203
you know. hypocritical thing.

00:41:15.303 --> 00:41:16.524
No. it's not cynical.

00:41:16.624 --> 00:41:18.006
See. these are naive--
I don't--

00:41:18.106 --> 00:41:19.407
I mean. I hate to tell
Mr. Rhodes.

00:41:19.507 --> 00:41:21.249
but these are-these are-
these are superficial. naive.

00:41:21.349 --> 00:41:24.613
and ra-rather fatuous
arguments.

00:41:24.713 --> 00:41:25.814
Uh. they may sell books.

00:41:25.914 --> 00:41:27.296
I hope he does sell
a lot of books.

00:41:27.396 --> 00:41:29.178
but. um...
[chuckles]

00:41:29.278 --> 00:41:31.861
...those-those--you know.
the role of the Saudis

00:41:31.961 --> 00:41:33.143
in global oil markets.

00:41:33.243 --> 00:41:35.185
the role of Saudi Arabia
in countering.

